BEGIN_PGML Note that a pound (lb) is a unit of force. It is approximately equal to 4.45 Newtons which is another unit of force. How many Newtons per square meter is 51.2 lbs per square inch? Look up other conversions as needed. [_]{'228'}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} \frac{51.2 \; \text{lbs}}{\; \text{inch}^2} \amp \approx \\ \frac{51.2 \; \text{lbs}}{\; \text{inch}^2} \cdot \frac{1.00 \; \text{N}}{4.45 \; \text{lbs}} \cdot \left(\frac{1.00 \; \text{inch}}{0.254 \; \text{m}}\right)^2 \amp \approx \\ \frac{51.2}{4.45 \cdot 0.0254^2} \frac{\text{lbs}}{\text{inch}^2} \cdot \frac{\text{N}}{\text{lbs}} \cdot \frac{\text{inch}^2}{\text{m}^2} \amp \approx \\ 17833 \frac{ \cancel{\text{lbs}}}{\bcancel{\; \text{inch}^2}} \cdot \frac{\text{N}}{\cancel{\text{lbs}}} \cdot \frac{\bcancel{\; \text{inch}^2}}{\text{m}^2} \amp \approx \\ \frac{17800 \; \text{N}}{\text{m}^2}. \end{aligned} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
