############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML For a particular cheesecake recipe there is [`15\bar{0}`] g of eggs and [`150\bar{0}`] g of cream cheese. Suppose you have [`35\bar{0}`] g of eggs and [`340\bar{0}`] g of cream cheese. How much of the egg and cream cheese can you use?
Egg: [_]{'340'}{4}
Cream cheese: [_]{'3400'}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The egg to cream cheese must be in a 1/10 ratio. We can check what the ratio of ingredients we have is.
[```\frac{35\bar{0} \; \text{g}}{340\bar{0} \; \text{g}} \approx 0.103```]
Because this is more than [`1/10=0.1`] we have more egg than we can use. Thus we will set up the 1/10 ratio using all of the cream cheese.
[``` \begin{aligned} \frac{1}{10} & = \frac{E \; \text{g}}{340\bar{0} \; \text{g}}.\\ \frac{1}{10} \cdot 340\bar{0} \; \text{g} & = \frac{E \; \text{g}}{340\bar{0} \; \text{g}} \cdot 340\bar{0} \; \text{g}.\\ 34\bar{0}.0 & = E \; \text{g}. \end{aligned} ```]
We can use 340 of the 350 grams of egg.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

